  "prompt": "Why is oxalic acid soluble in water?",
  "response": "Oxalic acid (C\u2082H\u2082O\u2084) is soluble in water primarily due to its ability to form hydrogen bonds with water molecules. Here are the key factors that contribute to its solubility:\n\n1. **Polarity**: Oxalic acid is a polar molecule, and water is a polar solvent. Polar solutes tend to dissolve well in polar solvents due to the \"like dissolves like\" principle. The polar nature of oxalic acid allows it to interact favorably with water molecules.\n\n2. **Hydrogen Bonding**: Oxalic acid contains two carboxyl groups (-COOH), which can form hydrogen bonds with water molecules. These hydrogen bonds are strong enough to overcome the lattice energy of the solid oxalic acid, allowing it to dissolve.\n\n3. **Ionization**: In water, oxalic acid can ionize to form oxalate ions (C\u2082O\u2084\u00b2\u207b) and hydrogen ions (H\u207a). This ionization process increases the interaction between oxalic acid and water, enhancing its solubility.\n\n4. **Intermolecular Forces**: The presence of dipole-dipole interactions between oxalic acid molecules and water molecules also contributes to the overall solubility.\n\nThese factors collectively enable oxalic acid to dissolve readily in water, making it quite soluble in aqueous solutions.",
